    <text id="B0178T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Black asks the Staunton Freedmen's Bureau agent [Thomas P. Jackson] to assist in
                    returning Robinson Jackson's daughter to Richmond. The daughter lives near
                    Staunton, but the circumstances are not entirely clear in the letter.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Agent Freedmens Bureau</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1868-02-25"><abbr expan="February">Feb</abbr><abbr expan="25, 1868">25/68</abbr></date>
                        <name type="place">Richmond</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir-</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I am requested to write to you by <hi rend="underline">Robinson</hi>
                    <hi rend="underline">Jackson</hi>, in regard to his daughter, concerning whom I
                    addressed you some weeks since. His daughter is named <hi rend="underline"
                        >Easter</hi>
                    <hi rend="underline">Jackson</hi>, and resides, as you informed me, with a <hi
                        rend="underline">Mr. Kelloe</hi>, a few miles from Staunton. He wishes you
                    to have her delivered to your office as soon as possible, as he has made
                    arrangements with the bearer of this - a train hand on the <abbr
                        expan="Virginia">Va</abbr> Central Railroad, for her, transportation to
                    Richmond, the bearer having kindly consented to bring her at a small cost to
                    said Jackson, who is a very poor man, and is not able to pay full fare for her.
                    He is under the impression that she would be of great service to himself and
                    wife in enabling them to maintain a livelihood. <hi rend="underline"
                    >Jackson</hi> is a very worthy colored man, and I would be obliged if you would
                    do all you can for him in this matter.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Respectfully</salute>
                    <signed><abbr expan="William">Wm</abbr> C Black<lb/>"New Nation" Printing Office</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
